I can only hope now to make more space for others who feel the same way I did, to make #neurodiversity “normal” so they can live and exist authentically. And fuck all these systems that make it hard for us to do so.

I lived 27 years of my life not knowing I had #ADHD. Before my diagnosis, I was in the worst mental and physical place I’ve ever been, and I truly believe my diagnosis and finding community saved my life.

Which is why we need more visibility and advocacy of neurodivergent people who are existing in this world that wasn’t made for them. Nothing is impossible for a neurodivergent person, but the systems and world in which they live make it seem impossible at times.
How does this play out in sex, relationships, and friendships? It’s a clusterfuck, for lack of better terms.

Listening to certain things, writing, sitting still, eating, etc. when your brain/body is in constant disregulation, and then have people telling you “lol good luck, just try harder” is very invalidating to our struggles and lack of control within our regulation.

Now also add this disregulation to the way you *feel* and *sense* the world. Some sounds are too loud. Textures can freak you out. You need some intensity in one area & then sensitivity in others. Sometimes you don’t know what the hell you need. Also sound exhausting? It is.

Sound disregulating? Yes. Sound exhausting? Also yes. Now imagine this disregulation permeating through every aspect of your life when you’re trying to live in a capitalistic, racist, ablest, and patriarchal society. It’s a lot. It’s not just a “focus or try harder” thing.

This is what makes #ADHD confusing and contradictory for so many people who don’t have it. Yes, we can hyperfocus and be totally available for a particular complex thing one moment, and then be absolutely checked out for the simplest thing the next moment.
This thread is great. People with ADHD don’t lack dopamine, we just have a harder time regulating it in our brains/bodies. It isn’t a lacking thing. It’s a regulation thing. https://t.co/DUmtMOyeiv
